The continued struggle of third parties traces to our use of the &quot;one-vote&quot; model of plurality voting.  As long as each citizen can only cast a single vote, their opinion is reduced to favor <i>one selection</i> at the consequence of all other options.  It is impossible to declare support (either equal or varied) for multiple candidates.<p>It remains a surprise to me that third parties do not raise the adoption of either score voting [1] or approval voting as their pinnacle issue.  Until it is plausible to cast a vote for third-party candidates without &quot;splitting the vote,&quot; third parties will remain far distant stars that exert the smallest of gravitational pulls on the two dominant parties.<p>The curiosity in all of this is that approval voting (effectively a binary-scale score voting) is the <i>natural</i> behavior of group decision making.  Even children use approval voting.<p><pre><code>    &quot;What movie do you want to see?&quot;
    &quot;Well, I&#x27;d see A, B, or C.  You?&quot;  
    &quot;I like C, D, or E.&quot;
    &quot;Great, we&#x27;ll see C.&quot;
</code></pre>
[1] <a href="http://electology.org/score-voting" rel="nofollow">http://electology.org/score-voting</a>
